<paragraph id="8BC236D91C59A350FD50A17DADAA8947" blockId="4.[714,1247,1336,1669]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D5A1C59A350FD50A17DAA088A3C" box="[740,875,1336,1363]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Celastraceae" genus="Brexia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Celastrales" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="apoda">
<emphasis id="B909EACB1C59A350FD50A17DAA088A3C" box="[740,875,1336,1363]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Brexia apoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small, sparsely branched treelet known from low elevation humid forest, from Mandena STF north to Vohipeno (Fig. 2). It can be recognized by its large leaves with usually spinose margins, its axillary, sessile to very short pedunculate inflorescences, often with a pair of small bracts at the apex of the peduncle, and flowers with deeply linear-lobed petaloid disc segments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC236D91C59A350FD50A26BADAA89EA" blockId="4.[714,1247,1336,1669]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">
